## 2.4.2 Executing tasks in parallel

**Q351. Concurrency vs parallelism in JSâ€”whatâ€™s the difference?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: JS is **single-threaded** on the main thread; it achieves **concurrency** by interleaving async work via the **event loop**. True **parallelism** needs separate threads/processes (e.g., **Web Workers**/Node workers). ğŸ“Œ For I/O (fetch, timers), start tasks together and let the runtime overlap them.

**Q352. How do I start multiple async tasks truly â€œin parallelâ€ (I/O)?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: Kick them off **before** awaiting, then join with `Promise.all`.

```js
const aP = fetch(aURL).then(r=>r.json());
const bP = fetch(bURL).then(r=>r.json());
const [a, b] = await Promise.all([aP, bP]);
```

ğŸ“Œ Starting then awaiting together avoids accidental **serialization**.

**Q353. How do I keep results in input order when completion order differs?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: `Promise.all` **preserves order by index**, regardless of finish times.
ğŸ“Œ Donâ€™t sort by completionâ€”use array positions to correlate inputs/outputs.

**Q354. How do I handle â€œsome succeed, some failâ€ without aborting all?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: Use **`Promise.allSettled`** or map each task to **catch** its own error.

```js
const out = await Promise.allSettled(tasks.map(t => t()));
// or
const out = await Promise.all(tasks.map(t => t().catch(e => ({ error: e }))));
```

ğŸ“Œ `allSettled` never rejects; inspect each entry.

**Q355. How do I cap concurrency (e.g., only 5 requests at a time)?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: Use a **pool/limiter**.

```js
async function mapLimit(items, limit, worker){
  const out = new Array(items.length); let i=0; const running = new Set();
  async function run(){
    if (i>=items.length) return;
    const idx = i++, p = worker(items[idx]).then(v => (out[idx]=v));
    running.add(p); p.finally(()=>running.delete(p)).finally(run);
  }
  for (let k=0;k<Math.min(limit, items.length);k++) run();
  await Promise.all([...running]);
  return out;
}
```

ğŸ“Œ Prevents **rate-limit** hits and memory spikes.

**Q356. I only need the *first* successful resultâ€”what pattern fits?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: Use **`Promise.any`** and **abort** the others if possible.

```js
const ctl = new AbortController();
const tryMirror = u => fetch(u, { signal: ctl.signal });
const winner = await Promise.any(urls.map(tryMirror));
ctl.abort(); // cancel losers if supported
```

ğŸ“Œ Pair with **AbortController** to free resources.

---

## 2.4.3 Fetch APIs ğŸ“Œ

**Q357. What does `fetch` return, and when does it reject?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: `fetch(url, init?)` returns a **Promise\<Response>**. It **rejects only** on **network errors/abort**â€”**not** for HTTP 4xx/5xx. Check `res.ok`/`res.status`.

```js
const res = await fetch(url);
if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${res.status}`);
```

ğŸ“Œ Many bugs come from assuming 404/500 **reject**â€”they donâ€™t.

**Q358. How do I read a response body? Can I read it twice?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: Use **one** of `.json()`, `.text()`, `.blob()`, `.arrayBuffer()` (or stream). A body is **consumable once**; subsequent reads fail.
ğŸ“Œ Clone first if you must read twice: `const copy = res.clone()`.

**Q359. How do I POST JSON correctly?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: Set `Content-Type` and `JSON.stringify` the body; handle non-OK.

```js
const res = await fetch(api, {
  method: 'POST',
  headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
  body: JSON.stringify(payload)
});
if (!res.ok) throw new Error(await res.text());
const data = await res.json();
```

ğŸ“Œ Server must actually expect JSON.

**Q360. How do I upload files or form data?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: Use **`FormData`**; **donâ€™t** set `Content-Type` manually.

```js
const fd = new FormData();
fd.append('avatar', file);
fd.append('name', 'Dilip');
await fetch('/upload', { method: 'POST', body: fd });
```

ğŸ“Œ The browser sets the correct **multipart boundary**.

**Q361. Whatâ€™s a clean way to build query strings?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: Use **`URL`** and **`URLSearchParams`**.

```js
const u = new URL('/search', origin);
u.search = new URLSearchParams({ q: 'js', page: 2 });
const res = await fetch(u);
```

ğŸ“Œ Handles encoding safely.

**Q362. How do I add a timeout/abort?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: Use **`AbortController`** (or `AbortSignal.timeout` where available).

```js
const ctl = new AbortController();
const t = setTimeout(()=>ctl.abort(), 8000);
try { await fetch(url, { signal: ctl.signal }); }
finally { clearTimeout(t); }
```

ğŸ“Œ Always clear timers; handle `AbortError`.

**Q363. CORS in a nutshellâ€”what should I know?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: The **same-origin policy** blocks reading cross-origin responses unless the server sends `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` (and more for **credentials**). Some requests trigger **preflight** (OPTIONS).
ğŸ“Œ `mode:"no-cors"` returns **opaque** responsesâ€”basically unreadable.

**Q364. How do cookies/credentials work with `fetch`?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: Set `credentials` appropriately:

* `'same-origin'` (default for same origin)
* `'include'` (send cookies cross-site if server allows)
  Server must send: `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true` and a **non-`*`** `Allow-Origin`.
  ğŸ“Œ Mind **`SameSite`** cookie attributes and **CSRF** tokens.

**Q365. What about redirects?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: `fetch` follows by default (`redirect:'follow'`). You can set `redirect:'error'` or `'manual'` (limited info exposed).
ğŸ“Œ Be careful with credentialed cross-origin redirects.

**Q366. Can I stream large responses progressively?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: Yesâ€”use **ReadableStream**.

```js
const res = await fetch(url);
const reader = res.body.getReader();
let received = 0;
for(;;){
  const {value, done} = await reader.read();
  if (done) break;
  received += value.byteLength; // process chunk
}
```

ğŸ“Œ Good for **large files** or **NDJSON**.

**Q367. Can I track upload progress with `fetch`?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: Browser `fetch` still lacks **upload progress events** in most cases. Use **XHR** for granular progress, or **streams** where supported.
ğŸ“Œ For downloads, stream reading allows manual progress.

**Q368. How does HTTP caching interact with `fetch`?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: Respect server headers: `Cache-Control`, `ETag`, `Last-Modified`. Or use the **Cache Storage API** (often via a **Service Worker**) for app-controlled caching.
ğŸ“Œ Prefer **revalidation** over blanket `no-store` for performance.

**Q369. What is `keepalive` (and `sendBeacon`) for unload-safe calls?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: `fetch(..., { keepalive:true })` or `navigator.sendBeacon` lets small requests outlive page unload (analytics/logs).
ğŸ“Œ There are **size limits**; keep payloads small and fire-and-forget.

**Q370. Security tips for `fetch` in SPAs?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: ğŸ“Œ Validate & sanitize inputs, use **CSRF tokens** for cookie-auth, prefer **token + `Authorization`** headers, lock down CORS, and never echo untrusted HTML. Use **`Content-Security-Policy`** to limit script sources.

---

## 2.4.4 `setTimeout` & `setInterval` ğŸ“Œ

**Q371. When should I prefer `setTimeout` over `setInterval`?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: `setInterval` can **pile up** if the handler is slower than the interval, causing drift and reentrancy. Prefer a **self-scheduling `setTimeout`** that schedules the **next** run after the current finishes.

```js
function tick(){
  doWork().finally(()=> setTimeout(tick, 1000));
}
setTimeout(tick, 1000);
```

ğŸ“Œ Gives you **backpressure** and less drift.

**Q372. Why isnâ€™t `setTimeout(fn, 0)` immediate?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: Timers are **macrotasks**; they run **after** the current stack and **after microtasks**. Browsers also apply **minimum clamping** (and heavier throttling in background tabs).
ğŸ“Œ For ASAP post-tick work, use **`queueMicrotask`**.

**Q373. How do microtasks relate to timers?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: Microtasks (e.g., **Promise callbacks**) run **before** timers.

```js
setTimeout(()=>console.log('timeout'));
Promise.resolve().then(()=>console.log('then'));
// logs: then â†’ timeout
```

ğŸ“Œ Use `queueMicrotask(fn)` for deterministic â€œafter current callâ€ behavior.

**Q374. How do I cancel timers reliably?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: Store the ID and call the clear function.

```js
const id = setInterval(tick, 500);
clearInterval(id);
```

ğŸ“Œ In modern runtimes, **`AbortSignal.timeout(ms)`** or `AbortController` can coordinate cancellation across APIs that support `signal`.

**Q375. When is `requestAnimationFrame` better than timers?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: For **visual updates**, `requestAnimationFrame` syncs with the displayâ€™s **refresh cycle** â†’ smoother animations and less jank.

```js
let running = true;
function step(t){ if (!running) return; update(); requestAnimationFrame(step); }
requestAnimationFrame(step);
```

ğŸ“Œ Cancel with `cancelAnimationFrame`.

**Q376. Show robust debounce and throttle with timers.**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer:

```js
// Debounce: run after inactivity window
function debounce(fn, wait=300){
  let t; return (...args)=>{ clearTimeout(t); t=setTimeout(()=>fn(...args), wait); };
}
// Throttle: run at most once per window
function throttle(fn, wait=300){
  let last=0, t;
  return (...args)=>{
    const now = Date.now(), remaining = wait - (now - last);
    if (remaining <= 0){ last = now; fn(...args); }
    else if (!t){ t=setTimeout(()=>{ t=null; last=Date.now(); fn(...args); }, remaining); }
  };
}
```

ğŸ“Œ Debounce = **group bursts**; Throttle = **limit frequency**.

---

## 2.4.5 Generators and Iterators

**Q377. What is a generator function and what does it return?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: A generator (`function*`) can **pause** with `yield` and **resume** via `.next()`. It returns an **iterator** (with `next/throw/return`) and is also **iterable** (has `[Symbol.iterator]`).

```js
function* ids(){ let i=0; while(true) yield i++; }
const g = ids(); g.next(); // {value:0, done:false}
```

ğŸ“Œ Great for **lazy sequences** and **custom control flow**.

**Q378. How does `yield*` work?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: It **delegates** to another iterable/generator, yielding its values seamlessly.

```js
function* g1(){ yield 1; yield 2; }
function* g2(){ yield* g1(); yield 3; }
[...g2()]; // [1,2,3]
```

ğŸ“Œ Useful for composing iterables.

**Q379. Practical uses for generators?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: ğŸ“Œ **Lazy data pipelines**, **in-order tree/graph traversal**, **flattening**, **back-pressure friendly** processing, and implementing **finite state machines**.

```js
function* inorder(node){ if (!node) return; yield* inorder(node.left); yield node.val; yield* inorder(node.right); }
```

**Q380. How do I make any object iterable?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: Define `[Symbol.iterator]()` to return an iterator.

```js
const range = {
  from:1, to:3,
  [Symbol.iterator](){ let i=this.from; return { next:()=>({ value:i, done: i++>this.to }) }; }
};
[...range]; // [1,2,3]
```

ğŸ“Œ Enables `for...of`, spread, destructuring.

**Q381. Whatâ€™s the difference between generators and async generators?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: **Async generators** (`async function*`) yield **Promises** and are consumed with **`for await...of`**.

```js
async function* stream(urls){ for (const u of urls) yield fetch(u).then(r=>r.text()); }
for await (const text of stream(urls)) { /* ... */ }
```

ğŸ“Œ Fit for **incremental async** data.

**Q382. Can I send values *into* a generator?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: Yesâ€”`gen.next(value)` passes `value` back into the paused `yield` expression.

```js
function* echo(){ const x = yield "send me"; return x; }
const g = echo(); g.next();        // {value:"send me"}
g.next(42);                        // returns {value:42, done:true}
```

ğŸ“Œ Enables **two-way** communication.

**Q383. Do generators replace async/await?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: Not anymore. Generators once powered async via â€œcoâ€ libraries, but **`async/await`** is now standard. Generators shine for **lazy synchronous** flows and **custom iteration**.
ğŸ“Œ Use **async generators** for streaming async sequences.

**Q384. Any pitfalls with generators?**
ğŸ‘‰ Answer: They hold **internal state** (not reentrant), can be **partially consumed**, and errors thrown in them must be handled. ğŸ“Œ Document consumption contract (single pass, restart by creating a new iterator).
